{"cursor":"37679","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Taxobox |image = Saint johns wart flowers.jpg |regnum = Plantae\n|unranked_divisio = Angiosperms |unranked_classis = Eudicots |unranked_ordo =\nRosids |ordo = Malpighiales |familia = Hypericaceae |genus = [[Hypericum]]\n|species = 'H. perforatum' |binomial = Hypericum perforatum\n|binomial_authority = L.\n|}}\n\n'St John's wort' (traditionally ; now in some dialects) is the plant species\n'Hypericum perforatum', and is also known as 'Tipton's weed', 'rosin rose',\n'goatweed', 'chase-devil', or 'Klamath weed'. [http://pharmaxchange.info/press/2012/12/pharmacognosy-of-st-\njohns-wort/ Pharmacognosy of St. John's Wort]\n\nWith qualifiers, St John's wort is used to refer to any species of the genus\n[[Hypericum]]. Therefore, H. perforatum is sometimes called 'common St John's\nwort' or 'perforate St John's wort' to differentiate it. The species of\nHypericum are classified in the Hypericaceae family, having previously been\nclassified as Guttiferae or Clusiaceae. Approximately 370\nspecies of the genus Hypericum exist worldwide with a native geographical\ndistribution including temperate and subtropical regions of North America,\nEurope, Turkey, Russia, India, China and Brazil.\n\nSt John's wort is widely known as an herbal medicine for treating\ndepression.\n","linknr":761,"url":"Saint_John's_wort","recorded":1362373086,"links":66,"instances":["pharmacy","mood","pharmacology","symptom","botany","pharmacy"],"pdf":["http://www.herbological.com/images/SJW_table.pdf","http://www.invasive.org/weedcd/pdfs/feis/Hypericumperforatum.pdf","http://www.invasive.org/weedcd/pdfs/feis/Hypericumperforatum.pdf","http://www.wcrx.com/pdfs/pi/pi_estrace_wc_imprint.pdf","http://www.wcrx.com/pdfs/pi/pi_estrace_wc_imprint.pdf"],"categories":["Hypericum|perforatum","Flora of Europe|Saint John's wort","Flora of Estonia|Saint John's wort","Flora of the United Kingdom|Saint John's wort","Garden plants of Europe|Saint John's w